o general and do not account for the variations that occur within complex societies such as china or the united states fukuyama has also realized that democracy is not always a necessary ingredient for good governance and in some cases authoritarian countries govern more effectively than their democratic counterparts the governance project was launched in january 2012 at fsi's center on democracy development and the rule of law to engage scholars around the world in the exercise of evaluating the quality of state institutions and government effectiveness over the next year workshops at stanford and in china will bring governance experts together to showcase the ongoing work in this field and contribute original scholarship to a working paper series case studies of china and the united states will conceptualize and measure state performance in the world's largest economies comparing and contrasting both models to better understand the inner workings of governance to learn more about the governance project please visit http governanceproject stanford edu search aparc search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages news of interest stanford university commemorates korean war 60th anniversary may 27 2010 ksp press release shorenstein aparc launches the annual stanford kyoto dialogue focusing on energy and the environment september 10 2009 announcement asia health policy program launches working paper series december 11 2008 ahpp news new course on north korea profiled in stanford magazine march 19 2008 shorenstein aparc fsi stanford ksp news shorenstein aparc releases two major new books through stanford university press april 5 2006 news new post doc fellowships sprie fellows at stanford 2005 2006 december 17 2004 sprie news support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 9741 fax 650 725 2592 mail c